    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sept. 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Dyer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>You have sent us a most magnificent supply of Australian leaves, &amp; Frank was hard at work all yesterday in removing bloom &amp; weighing lots of leaves in our grand new chemical balance. The poor mertensia looks very bad &amp; I fear will never revive, &amp; this goes to my heart, as it seems to have splendid bloom.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 have] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.1 a] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘yester’ </note>
            </div>

        </div>
             
             
             <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11149.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. T. Thiselton-Dyer, 22 September 1877</ref>.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had requested leaves from <hi rend="italic">Eucalyptus globulus</hi> and an Australian acacia in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11149.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to W. T. Thiselton-Dyer, 22 September 1877</ref>. He also accepted Thiselton-Dyer’s offer of an oysterleaf plant (<hi rend="italic">Mertensia maritima</hi>).  He was conducting experiments with <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> into the function of bloom.</note>
            </div> 
     
     
     
